    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided sections of the S-1 filing, here is the breakdown of the share counts, capitalization structure, and the specific figures needed to calculate the implied per-share valuation.\n\n### 1. Total Share Count for Implied Valuation (Pro Forma & Pre-Offering)\nTo calculate the implied equity valuation at the time of the IPO, you must use the **Pro Forma** or **Pre-Offering** share counts. These figures assume the completion of the IPO structural conditions, including the 5-for-1 "2026 Stock Split," the conversion of all Preferred Stock, and the reclassification of all Class C shares into Class A shares. \n\n*   **Pro Forma Outstanding (from Capitalization Table):**\n    *   **Class A:** 6,824,581,339 shares\n    *   **Class B:** 5,695,729,430 shares\n    *   **Class C:** 0 shares (reclassified into Class A)\n    *   **Total Pro Forma Outstanding:** **12,520,310,769 shares**\n*   **Pre-Offering Outstanding (as of May 1, 2026, from Beneficial Ownership Table):**\n    *   **Class A:** 6,932,508,000 shares\n    *   **Class B:** 5,602,790,410 shares\n    *   **Total Pre-Offering Outstanding:** **12,535,298,410 shares**\n\n*(Note: To get the exact **post-offering** total share count for the final valuation, you would add the actual number of Class A shares sold in the IPO to the pre-offering base. The filing leaves the exact IPO price and offering size blank in the preamble templates pending final pricing).*\n\n### 2. Actual Outstanding Shares by Class (Historical Balance Sheets)\nThe filing provides actual historical outstanding shares (presented in millions) prior to the IPO conversions and stock splits. \n\n**As of March 31, 2026:**\n*   **Class A:** 2,883 million (or 2,884M per roll-forward table)\n*   **Class B:** 2,421 million (or 2,418M per roll-forward table)\n*   **Class C:** 494 million (or 497M per roll-forward table)\n*   **Class D:** 0 shares\n*   **Total Actual Outstanding:** **~5,799 million shares**\n\n**As of December 31, 2025:**\n*   **Class A:** 1,952 million (or 1,954M per text)\n*   **Class B:** 643 million (or 644M per text)\n*   **Class C:** 484 million (or 482M per text)\n*   **Class D:** 0 shares\n*   **Total Actual Outstanding:** **~3,079 million shares**\n\n**As of December 31, 2024:**\n*   **Class A:** 1,832 million\n*   **Class B:** 768 million\n*   **Class C:** 421 million (or 423M per roll-forward table)\n*   **Class D:** 0 shares\n*   **Total Actual Outstanding:** **~3,021 million shares**\n\n### 3. Total Authorized Common Stock (Post-IPO Charter)\nUpon completion of the offering, the company\'s charter authorizes a massive pool of common stock to accommodate future grants, conversions, and the multi-class structure:\n*   **Class A:** 36,132,150,000 shares (36,132 million)\n*   **Class B:** 6,125,000,000 shares (6,125 million)\n*   **Class C:** 10,000,000,000 shares (10,000 million)\n*   **Class D:** 2,400,000,000 shares (2,400 million)\n*   **Total Authorized Common Stock:** **54,657,150,000 shares**\n\n### 4. Key Caveats for Valuation Calculations\nIf you are building a valuation model based on this data, keep the following structural nuances in mind:\n*   **Dual-Class Voting Discrepancy:** While Class A and Class B shares likely have the same *economic* value per share, they have vastly different *voting* power. Class A holds **1 vote per share**, while Class B holds **10 votes per share**. Class B shareholders also hold special protective provisions (e.g., the right to elect 51% of the board and veto power over Elon Musk\'s removal).\n*   **Excluded Shares (Overhang):** The "Total Pro Forma" share count explicitly **excludes** shares reserved for future issuance. As of March 31, 2026, the company reserved an additional **9.35 billion Class A**, **3.72 billion Class B**, and **7.62 billion Class C** shares for outstanding stock options, RSUs, future equity plans, and low/high-vote preferred stock conversions. If calculating a *fully diluted* valuation, these reserved shares must be factored in.\n*   **Underwriter Options:** The final share count will increase if the underwriters exercise their option to purchase additional shares (the "greenshoe" option), the exact amount of which is left blank in the prospectus summary.',
